<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many bricks do I need per square foot?", answer: "A standard brick (8 inches x 2.25 inches x 3.5 inches) with a 3/8-inch mortar joint covers approximately 6.75 bricks per square foot of wall area. This is calculated by dividing 144 square inches by the area of one brick plus its mortar joint (8.375 inches x 2.625 inches = 21.98 square inches). Always add 10% for waste from cuts, breakage, and defective units." },
  { question: "How many concrete blocks per square foot?", answer: "Standard 8-inch CMU (Concrete Masonry Unit) blocks measuring 16 inches x 8 inches with 3/8-inch mortar joints require approximately 1.125 blocks per square foot. This equals about 113 blocks per 100 square feet of wall area. The same count applies to 12-inch-wide CMU blocks since only the face dimensions (16 x 8) determine the count, not the wall thickness." },
  { question: "How much mortar do I need for a brick wall?", answer: "For standard bricks, one bag of premixed mortar (typically 60 or 80 lbs) covers approximately 130-150 bricks depending on joint thickness and technique. For CMU blocks, one bag covers approximately 30-40 square feet of wall area. Mortar requirements increase with wider joints and less-experienced bricklayers. Always have extra mortar on hand, as running out mid-course requires careful color matching." },
  { question: "How do I account for window and door openings?", answer: "Calculate the total wall area (length x height) and subtract the area of all openings (windows, doors, and other cutouts) in square feet. Enter the total opening area in the Openings field. The calculator will subtract this from the gross wall area before computing the number of bricks or blocks needed. Dont forget to account for lintels above openings, which may require additional materials." },
  { question: "What is the difference between modular and standard bricks?", answer: "Standard bricks measure 8 inches x 2.25 inches x 3.5 inches. Modular bricks measure 7.625 inches x 2.25 inches x 3.625 inches and are designed so that three courses of brick plus three mortar joints equal exactly 8 inches in height, making it easier to coordinate with 8-inch CMU block coursing. Modular bricks require slightly more units per square foot (about 6.86 vs 6.75) but simplify layout at corners and openings." }
]) %>

